answers.body_markdown:
You could use a [branch reset group](https://www.regular-expressions.info/branchreset.html) `(?|` and add a space between the digits and the TXT.

    (?|TXT (?&lt;number&gt;[[0-9]+)|(?&lt;number&gt;[[0-9]+) TXT)

[Regex demo](https://regex101.com/r/DXik6V/1) | [Php demo](https://3v4l.org/Hh3s0)


For example

    $re = &#39;/(?|TXT (?&lt;number&gt;[[0-9]+)|(?&lt;number&gt;[[0-9]+) TXT)/&#39;;
    $str = &#39;TXT 4
    4 TXT&#39;;
    
    preg_match_all($re, $str, $matches);
    print_r($matches[&quot;number&quot;]);

Output

    Array
    (
        [0] =&gt; 4
        [1] =&gt; 4
    )

To write 2 groups with the same name you need to use the `(?J)` inline flag:

    &#39;/(?J)TXT(?&lt;number&gt;[0-9]+)|(?&lt;number&gt;[0-9]+)TXT/&#39;

See the [regex demo][1]

[Documentation][2]:

&gt; `J (PCRE_INFO_JCHANGED)`&lt;br/&gt;
The `(?J)` internal option setting changes the local `PCRE_DUPNAMES` option. Allow duplicate names for subpatterns. As of PHP 7.2.0 *J* is supported as modifier as well.

[PHP demo][3]:

    $regex = &#39;/(?J)TXT(?&lt;number&gt;[0-9]+)|(?&lt;number&gt;[0-9]+)TXT/&#39;;
    if (preg_match_all($regex, &quot;TXT123 and 456TXT1&quot;, $matches, PREG_SET_ORDER, 0)) {
        foreach ($matches as $m) {
            echo $m[&quot;number&quot;] . PHP_EOL;
        }
    }

Note that in your case, you do not need the groups:

    &#39;/TXT\K[0-9]+|[0-9]+(?=TXT)/&#39;

The lookarounds will also do the job here.

  [1]: https://regex101.com/r/htvF79/1
  [2]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/reference.pcre.pattern.modifiers.php
  [3]: https://3v4l.org/4MHGa

Starting with iOS 13, the system will automatically prompt the user to grant an app permission to use bluetooth when the app tries to scan for or connect to a bluetooth device.  The message in the generic dialog may be augmented with a custom message by the following entry in Info.plist:

	&lt;key&gt;NSBluetoothAlwaysUsageDescription&lt;/key&gt;
	&lt;string&gt;This app uses bluetooth to perform XYZ functions.&lt;/string&gt;

If the user denies permission when presented this dialog, the app will not be able to scan for or connect to bluetooth devices.  It is possible that your app presented this dialog and you did not notice and accidentally denied permission.

To check this, you can go to Settings &gt; Privacy &gt; Bluetooth and check if your app is granted bluetooth permission.

